---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  { question: "What is the difference between SonarQube Community and Developer edition?", answer: "Community Edition is free and open-source. It supports single-branch analysis for Java, JavaScript, Python, and 15+ languages, making it sufficient for most open-source projects and small teams. Developer Edition adds multi-branch and pull request analysis, deeper security rules (taint analysis), and additional language support. It is a paid tier aimed at professional teams that need per-PR quality gates." },
  { question: "How do I configure a quality gate to fail CI?", answer: "In the SonarQube UI, go to Quality Gates and create or edit a gate. Add conditions such as 'Coverage on new code is less than 80%' or 'Reliability Rating on new code is worse than A'. Then in your GitHub Actions workflow, add sonarcloud-github-action or sonar-scanner with the sonar.qualitygate.wait=true property. The step will exit with a non-zero code when the gate fails, blocking the merge." },
  { question: "What is technical debt in SonarQube?", answer: "Technical debt is an estimate of the effort (in minutes or hours) required to fix all code smells in the codebase. SonarQube calculates it using a SQALE method: each code smell type has a remediation cost, and the total is summed. The Maintainability Rating (A–E) is derived from the debt ratio — debt divided by total development cost. It gives teams a concrete, actionable number rather than a vague quality score." },
  { question: "What is the difference between SonarCloud and SonarQube?", answer: "SonarQube is self-hosted software you run on your own infrastructure (or Docker). SonarCloud is the SaaS version hosted by Sonar. SonarCloud is free for public repositories and requires no server maintenance, making it ideal for open-source projects. SonarQube gives you full control over data, custom plugins, and on-premise deployment needed for compliance-sensitive environments." },
  { question: "How do I integrate SonarQube with GitHub Actions?", answer: "Add a workflow step that runs sonar-scanner with your project key and host URL. For SonarCloud, use the SonarSource/sonarcloud-github-action action. Pass SONAR_TOKEN as a secret. Set sonar.projectKey, sonar.organization (Cloud only), sonar.sources, and sonar.javascript.lcov.reportPaths for coverage. Add sonar.qualitygate.wait=true to make the step block until the quality gate result is returned." },
  { question: "What are code smells vs bugs vs vulnerabilities in SonarQube?", answer: "Bugs are code that is likely to behave unexpectedly or produce wrong results at runtime — for example, a null dereference or an unreachable catch block. Vulnerabilities are security weaknesses that an attacker could exploit, such as SQL injection or hardcoded credentials. Code smells are maintainability issues that are not immediately harmful but increase technical debt — duplicated code, overly complex methods, or unused variables." },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="SonarQube: Code Quality Gates, Setup & CI Integration Guide"
  description="SonarQube setup guide: install with Docker, configure quality gates, integrate with GitHub Actions, fix code smells, track technical debt, and use SonarCloud for free."
  tool="SonarQube, code quality, quality gates, SonarCloud, static analysis, technical debt, CI integration"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "SonarQube: Code Quality Gates, Setup & CI Integration Guide",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/sonarqube-code-quality",
    "description": "SonarQube setup guide: install with Docker, configure quality gates, integrate with GitHub Actions, fix code smells, track technical debt, and use SonarCloud for free.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">SonarQube: Code Quality Gates, Setup & CI Integration Guide</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">SonarQube is the industry-standard static analysis platform for tracking bugs, vulnerabilities, code smells, and test coverage across your codebase. This guide covers Docker setup, quality gate configuration, GitHub Actions integration, and how to read the reports that actually matter.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Docker quickstart in under 5 minutes</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> GitHub Actions CI integration</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> SonarCloud free for public repos</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Quality gate pass/fail automation</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">What Is SonarQube (vs ESLint and Semgrep)?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">ESLint catches style and syntax issues within JavaScript files. Semgrep is a pattern-matching security scanner. SonarQube operates at a higher level: it tracks metrics over time, computes technical debt, measures test coverage, and enforces quality gates that block deployments. Unlike one-off linters, SonarQube maintains a persistent database of your project history so you can see whether quality is trending up or down.</p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800 text-white">
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Tool</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Primary Use</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Tracks History</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Quality Gates</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">ESLint</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">JS/TS style & syntax</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">No</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Exit code only</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Semgrep</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Security patterns</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Limited</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Rule-based only</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">SonarQube</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Full quality platform</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Yes (DB)</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Rich, metric-based</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Docker Quickstart</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-3">The fastest way to run SonarQube locally is with Docker Compose. This starts the server and a PostgreSQL database:</p>
  <pre class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code class="text-green-400"># docker-compose.yml
version: "3"
services:
  sonarqube:
    image: sonarqube:community
    ports:
      - "9000:9000"
    environment:
      SONAR_JDBC_URL: jdbc:postgresql://db:5432/sonar
      SONAR_JDBC_USERNAME: sonar
      SONAR_JDBC_PASSWORD: sonar
    depends_on:
      - db
  db:
    image: postgres:15
    environment:
      POSTGRES_USER: sonar
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: sonar
      POSTGRES_DB: sonar

# Start with:
docker compose up -d
# Open http://localhost:9000 — default login admin/admin</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Connecting Your Project</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-3">After logging in, create a project and generate a token. Then run sonar-scanner from your project root:</p>
  <pre class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code class="text-green-400">npx sonar-scanner \
  -Dsonar.projectKey=my-project \
  -Dsonar.sources=src \
  -Dsonar.host.url=http://localhost:9000 \
  -Dsonar.token=YOUR_TOKEN \
  -Dsonar.javascript.lcov.reportPaths=coverage/lcov.info</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Quality Gates: Pass/Fail Criteria</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">A quality gate is a set of conditions your project must meet to pass. The built-in "Sonar Way" gate checks new code only — this is intentional: it lets you improve without being blocked by legacy debt. Common conditions to add:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-1">
    <li>Coverage on new code &gt;= 80%</li>
    <li>Duplicated lines on new code &lt;= 3%</li>
    <li>Reliability Rating on new code = A (no new bugs)</li>
    <li>Security Rating on new code = A (no new vulnerabilities)</li>
    <li>Maintainability Rating on new code = A</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">GitHub Actions Integration</h2>
  <pre class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code class="text-green-400"># .github/workflows/sonar.yml
name: SonarCloud Analysis
on: [push, pull_request]
jobs:
  sonar:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          fetch-depth: 0          # full history for blame data
      - uses: actions/setup-node@v4
        with: &#123; node-version: 20 &#125;
      - run: npm ci && npm test -- --coverage
      - uses: SonarSource/sonarcloud-github-action@master
        env:
          GITHUB_TOKEN: $&#123;&#123; secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN &#125;&#125;
          SONAR_TOKEN: $&#123;&#123; secrets.SONAR_TOKEN &#125;&#125;
        with:
          args: >
            -Dsonar.qualitygate.wait=true</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Reading the Reports</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">The SonarQube dashboard splits issues into four categories:</p>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800 text-white">
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Category</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">What it Means</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Rating Scale</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Bugs</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Runtime defects</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">A (0) → E (many)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Vulnerabilities</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Security weaknesses</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">A (0) → E (critical)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Code Smells</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Maintainability debt</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Time estimate</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Coverage</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">% lines tested</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Percentage</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">SonarQube vs SonarCloud vs SonarLint</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">SonarLint is an IDE plugin (VS Code, IntelliJ) that gives real-time feedback as you type — it is the fastest feedback loop. SonarQube is self-hosted and used in CI pipelines. SonarCloud is the hosted SaaS version, free for public repos. In practice, teams run SonarLint locally for immediate feedback and SonarCloud/SonarQube in CI as a gate.</p>

  <ToolPageCta />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
</BaseLayout>
